<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="1384" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[166,777,1207,2091]" box="[168,277,1207,1231]" pageId="9" pageNumber="1384">
<figureCitation box="[168,277,1207,1231]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="9.[813,874,587,607]" captionTargetBox="[813,1420,160,563]" captionTargetId="figure-765@9.[813,1420,160,563]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figure 5. Birds of Bogotá’s Savannah. A. Rallus semiplumbeus. B. Gallinago nobilis. C. Breeding evidence ofG.nobilis in ESNR.D. Sturnella magna." pageId="9" pageNumber="1384">Figure 5D</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[166,777,1207,2091]" pageId="9" pageNumber="1384">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[168,318,1246,1270]" pageId="9" pageNumber="1384">New records.</emphasis>
Several adults and chicks have been heard and seen, hiding in the grasslands of the ESNR. We recorded this species in systematic surveys in all the samples since the beginning of our study.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[166,777,1207,2091]" pageId="9" pageNumber="1384">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[168,330,1385,1409]" pageId="9" pageNumber="1384">Identification.</emphasis>
Adults with a sturdy body, long pointed beak, long legs, and short tail; head with broad blackish and whitish brown lists; the dorsal region is dark-brown, barred with black; throat, chest, and belly bright yellow with a black V-shaped spot; ventral region dark, mottled brown in young birds.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="1384" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[166,777,1207,2091]" pageId="9" pageNumber="1384">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[168,280,1592,1616]" pageId="9" pageNumber="1384">Remarks.</emphasis>
On 
<date box="[322,455,1592,1616]" pageId="9" pageNumber="1384" value="2018-07-10">10 July 2018</date>
, we observed a nest with three chicks devoid of feathers and down and with closed eyes. On 
<date box="[207,387,1659,1683]" pageId="9" pageNumber="1384" value="2018-10-31">31 October 2018</date>
, we recorded a nest with 
<specimenCount box="[662,774,1659,1684]" pageId="9" pageNumber="1384" type="egg">three eggs</specimenCount>
(
<quantity box="[175,281,1693,1717]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.774" pageId="9" pageNumber="1384" unit="mm" value="27.74">27.74 mm</quantity>
× 
<quantity box="[307,416,1693,1717]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.011" pageId="9" pageNumber="1384" unit="mm" value="20.11">20.11 mm</quantity>
). The species is threatened by ag- ricultural activities (use of pesticides and herbicides) and livestock. However, the population trend is currently increasing (Birdlife 
<bibRefCitation author="International" box="[367,569,1793,1817]" pageId="9" pageNumber="1384" pagination="22735434" refId="ref12363" refString="BirdLife International (2018) Sturnella magna. The IUCN Red List of threatened species 2018: e. T 22735434 A 131853051. https: // doi. org / 10.2305 / IUCN. UK. 2018 - 2. RLTS. T 22735434 A 155622113. en. Accessed on: 2019 - 6 - 3." type="book chapter" year="2018">International 2018</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingRegion box="[617,694,1793,1817]" country="Colombia" name="Bogota" pageId="9" pageNumber="1384">Bogotá</collectingRegion>
and its surroundings, populations have been undergoing a reduction in their abundance as a result of the loss of grasslands for housing and exotic flower crops (
<bibRefCitation author="Stiles FG &amp; Rosselli L &amp; De la Zerda S" pageId="9" pageNumber="1384" pagination="58" refId="ref13708" refString="Stiles FG, Rosselli L, De la Zerda S (2017) Changes over 26 years in the avifauna of the Bogota Region, Colombia: Has climate change become important? Frontiers in Ecology and Evolution 5: 58. https: // doi. org / 10.3389 / fevo. 2017.00058." type="journal article" year="2017">Stiles et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
). As part of the conservation strategy for this species, grassland areas without contaminants where the species can nest can be increased (
<bibRefCitation author="Jaster LA &amp; Jensen WE &amp; Lanyon WE" box="[540,723,1994,2019]" pageId="9" pageNumber="1384" refId="ref13083" refString="Jaster LA, Jensen WE, Lanyon WE (2012) Eastern Meadowlark (Sturnella magna), version 2.0. In: Rodewald PG (Ed.) The birds of North America. Cornell Lab of Ornithology, New York. https: // doi. org / 10.2173 / bna. 160. Accessed on: 2019 - 6 - 1." type="book" year="2012">Jaster et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="1384" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[166,777,1207,2091]" pageId="9" pageNumber="1384">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[168,317,2033,2057]" pageId="9" pageNumber="1384">Distribution.</emphasis>
North and Central America and northeastern South America.
</paragraph>
